      <h2>Bar Refrigerator Types and Their Repair Needs</h2>
      <p><strong>1. Under-Counter Bar Refrigerators</strong></p>
      <p>Under-counter bar refrigerators are a popular choice for bars and restaurants due to their space-saving design and
        easy accessibility. These units fit snugly beneath the counter, allowing bartenders to quickly grab beverages and
        ingredients without leaving their station. Common repair needs for under-counter bar refrigerators include issues with
        the thermostat, which can lead to improper cooling and spoilage of stored items. Problems with the door seal are also
        frequent, resulting in energy loss and inefficient cooling. Regular maintenance, such as cleaning the condenser coils
        and checking the refrigerant levels, can help prevent these issues and ensure the unit operates efficiently.</p>
      <p><strong>2. Back Bar Coolers</strong></p>
      <p>Back bar coolers are designed to store and display beverages behind the bar, providing easy access for bartenders and
        an attractive display for customers. These coolers often feature glass doors and adjustable shelving, making them
        ideal for showcasing a variety of drinks. Common repair needs for back bar coolers include malfunctioning compressors,
        which can lead to inadequate cooling and potential beverage spoilage. Additionally, issues with the internal lighting
        system can affect the display's appeal. Routine maintenance, such as cleaning the evaporator fan and inspecting the
        door gaskets, can help keep back bar coolers running smoothly and looking their best.</p>
      <p><strong>3. Kegerators</strong></p>
      <p>Kegerators are specialized refrigerators designed to store and dispense kegs of beer, making them a staple in many
        bars and restaurants. These units typically include a refrigeration system, a tap, and a CO2 tank to keep the beer
        carbonated and fresh. Common repair needs for kegerators include issues with the CO2 system, such as leaks or
        regulator malfunctions, which can affect the quality of the beer. Problems with the cooling system, such as a faulty
        thermostat or compressor, can also impact the beer's temperature and taste. Regular maintenance, including cleaning
        the beer lines and checking the CO2 levels, is essential to keep kegerators functioning properly and serving up
        perfect pints.</p>
      <p><strong>4. Wine Coolers</strong></p>
      <p>Wine coolers are designed to store wine at optimal temperatures, preserving its flavor and aroma. These units often
        feature dual temperature zones, allowing for the storage of both red and white wines at their respective ideal
        temperatures. Common repair needs for wine coolers include thermostat issues, which can lead to temperature
        fluctuations and potentially spoil the wine. Problems with the cooling system, such as a failing compressor or
        evaporator fan, can also affect the unit's performance. Regular maintenance, including cleaning the condenser coils
        and ensuring proper ventilation, can help prevent these issues and keep wine coolers operating efficiently.</p>
      <p><strong>5. Display Refrigerators</strong></p>
      <p>Display refrigerators are used in bars and restaurants to showcase a variety of beverages and attract customers with
